Description: General options provided by the Frama-C kernel

Most options of the form '-option-name' and without any parameter
have an opposite with the name '-no-option-name'.

Options taking a string as argument should preferably be written
-option-name="argument".

***** LIST OF AVAILABLE OPTIONS:

-permissive         perform less verifications on validity of command-line
                    options
-session <dir>      set the Frama-C session directory to <dir>

*** ANALYSIS OPTIONS

-absolute-valid-range <min-max>  min and max must be integers in decimal,
                    hexadecimal (0x, 0X), octal (0o) or binary (0b) notation
                    and fit in 64 bits. Assume that that all absolute
                    addresses outside of the [min-max] range are invalid. In
                    the absence of this option, all absolute addresses are
                    assumed to be invalid (preferably use
                    -absolute-valid-range="min-max")
-lib-entry          run analysis for an incomplete application e.g. an API
                    call. See the -main option to set the entry point
                    (opposite option is -no-lib-entry)
-main <f>           use <f> as entry point for analysis. See "-lib-entry" if
                    this is not for a complete application. Defaults to main
                    (preferably use -main="f")
-safe-arrays        for multidimensional arrays or arrays that are fields
                    inside structs, assume that accesses are in bounds (set
                    by default, opposite option is -unsafe-arrays)
-unsafe-arrays      opposite of option -safe-arrays, whose help message
                    is:
                    for multidimensional arrays or arrays that are fields
                    inside structs, assume that accesses are in bounds
-unspecified-access  do not assume that read/write accesses occurring between
                    sequence points are separated (opposite option is
                    -no-unspecified-access)
-warn-invalid-bool  generate alarms when trap representations are read from
                    _Bool lvalues. (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-warn-invalid-bool)
-warn-invalid-pointer  generate alarms when invalid pointers are created.
                    (opposite option is -no-warn-invalid-pointer)
-warn-left-shift-negative  generate alarms for signed left shifts on negative
                    values. (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-warn-left-shift-negative)
-warn-pointer-downcast  generate alarms when a pointer is converted into an
                    integer but may not be in the range of the destination
                    type. (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-warn-pointer-downcast)
-warn-right-shift-negative  generate alarms for signed right shifts on
                    negative values. (opposite option is
                    -no-warn-right-shift-negative)
-warn-signed-downcast  generate alarms when signed downcasts may exceed the
                    destination range (opposite option is
                    -no-warn-signed-downcast)
-warn-signed-overflow  generate alarms for signed operations that overflow.
                    (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-warn-signed-overflow)
-warn-special-float <none|nan|non-finite>  generate alarms when special
                    floats are produced: never, only on NaN, or on infinite
                    floats and NaN (by default). (preferably use
                    -warn-special-float="none|nan|non-finite")
-warn-unaligned-pointer  generate alarms when unaligned pointers are created.
                    (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-warn-unaligned-pointer)
-warn-unsigned-downcast  generate alarms when unsigned downcasts may exceed
                    the destination range (opposite option is
                    -no-warn-unsigned-downcast)
-warn-unsigned-overflow  generate alarms for unsigned operations that
                    overflow (opposite option is -no-warn-unsigned-overflow)

*** COMPILATION DATABASE

-compilation-db <path>  when set, preprocessing of each file will include
                    corresponding flags (e.g. -I, -D) from the JSON
                    compilation database specified by <path>. If <path> is a
                    directory, use '<path>/compile_commands.json'. Disabled
                    by default.
-mopsa-db <path>    when set, the specified path (or <path>/mopsa-db.json, if
                    <path> is a directory) is loaded as a build database. If
                    '-mopsa-target' is not set, prints the list of targets in
                    the database and exits. Otherwise, '-mopsa-target' sets
                    the files to be parsed and preprocessing flags.
-mopsa-exclude-sources <file1,file2,...>  list of source files to be
                    blacklisted from the set computed by -mopsa-target, so
                    that Frama-C will not try to parse them. (preferably use
                    -mopsa-exclude-sources="file1,file2,...")
-mopsa-list-deps <target1,target2,...>  prints the sources (and relevant
                    preprocessing flags) used by target1,target2,..., then
                    exits. (preferably use
                    -mopsa-list-deps="target1,target2,...")
-mopsa-target <target1,target2,...>  name of the target(s) present in the
                    mopsa-db for which the list of sources should be parsed;
                    replaces any existing files in the command-line. Paths
                    are relative to the directory containing the mopsa
                    database, not PWD. Note that messages related to mopsa
                    databases are still emitted relative to Frama-C's PWD, as
                    usual. (preferably use
                    -mopsa-target="target1,target2,...")

*** CUSTOMIZING NORMALIZATION

-aggressive-merging  merge function definitions modulo renaming (defaults to
                    false) (opposite option is -no-aggressive-merging)
-allow-duplication  allow duplication of small blocks during normalization
                    (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-allow-duplication)
-asm-contracts      generate contracts for assembly code written according to
                    gcc's extended syntax (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-asm-contracts)
-asm-contracts-auto-validate  automatically mark contracts generated from asm
                    as valid (defaults to false) (opposite option is
                    -no-asm-contracts-auto-validate)
-asm-contracts-ensure-init  when contracts for assembly code are generated,
                    add postconditions stating that the output are
                    initialized. (opposite option is
                    -no-asm-contracts-ensure-init)
-collapse-call-cast  Allow some implicit casts between returned value of a
                    function and the lvalue it is assigned to. (set by
                    default, opposite option is -no-collapse-call-cast)
-constfold          fold all constant expressions in the code before analysis
                    (opposite option is -no-constfold)
-enums <default|gcc-enums|int|msvc|gcc-short-enums>  decide how enumerated
                    types should be represented:
                    - 'default' (default): chose between gcc or msvc
                    depending on the machdep
                    - 'int': treat everything as int (including enumerated
                    types with packed attribute)
                    - 'gcc-enums': use an unsigned integer type when no tag
                    has a negative value, and choose the smallest rank
                    possible starting from int (default gcc's behavior)
                    - 'gcc-short-enums': same behavior than 'gcc-enums' but
                    starting from char instead (gcc's -fshortenums option)
                    - 'msvc': same behavior than 'int'
-generated-spec-custom <c1:m1,c2:m2,...>  Fine-tune missing specification
                    generation by manually selecting modes for each clause.
                    Can be one of: frama-c, acsl, safe, skip or the name of a
                    custom registered mode. Do not use skip mode for assigns
                    unless you know what you are doing! See user manual for
                    more information. (preferably use
                    -generated-spec-custom="c1:m1,c2:m2,...")
-generated-spec-mode <mode>  Select which mode will be used to generate
                    missing specifications. Can be one of: frama-c, acsl,
                    safe, or the name of a custom registered mode (defaults
                    to frama-c). See user manual for more information.
                    (preferably use -generated-spec-mode="mode")
-initialized-padding-locals  Implicit initialization of locals sets padding
                    bits to 0. If false, padding bits are left uninitialized.
                    Defaults to true. (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-initialized-padding-locals)
-inline-calls <f1, ..., fn>  inline calls to functions f1, ..., fn
                    (preferably use -inline-calls="f1, ..., fn")
-inline-stmt-contracts  transforms requires/ensures clauses of statement
                    contracts into plain assertions, enabling their
                    verification by plug-ins with incomplete support for
                    statement contracts. (opposite option is
                    -no-inline-stmt-contracts)
-keep-switch        keep switch statements despite -simplify-cfg (opposite
                    option is -no-keep-switch)
-keep-unused-functions <none|user-specified|all|all_debug>  whether to keep
                    unused function declarations: none, only functions with
                    user specifications (by default; excludes stdlib and
                    generated functions), or keep all unused functions
                    (all_debug also includes compiler builtins) (preferably
                    use
                    -keep-unused-functions="none|user-specified|all|all_debug")
-keep-unused-types  keep unused types (false by default) (opposite option is
                    -remove-unused-types)
-remove-exn         transforms throw and try/catch statements to normal C
                    functions. Disabled by default, unless input source
                    language has has an exception mechanism. (opposite option
                    is -no-remove-exn)
-remove-inlined <f1, ..., fn>  remove inlined functions f1, ..., fn, which
                    must have been given to -inline-calls. Warning: this does
                    not check if the given functions were fully inlined.
                    (preferably use -remove-inlined="f1, ..., fn")
-remove-unused-types  (set by default) opposite of option -keep-unused-types,
                    whose help message is:
                    keep unused types (false by default)
-simplify-cfg       remove break, continue and switch statements before
                    analyses (opposite option is -no-simplify-cfg)
-simplify-trivial-loops  simplify trivial loops, such as do ... while(0)
                    loops (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-simplify-trivial-loops)
-ulevel <l>         unfold loops n times (defaults to 0) before analyzes. A
                    negative value hides loop unfold annotations.
-ulevel-force       ignore loop unfold "done" specifications (force
                    unfolding). (opposite option is -no-ulevel-force)
-variadic-strict    display warnings about non-portable implicit casts in the
                    calls of standard variadic functions, i.e. casts between
                    distinct integral types which have the same size and
                    signedness (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-variadic-strict)
-variadic-translation  translate variadic functions and calls to semantic
                    equivalents with only a fixed list of formal parameters
                    (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-variadic-translation)

*** DEBUG

-check              performs consistency checks over the Abstract Syntax Tree
                    (opposite option is -no-check)
-copy               always perform a copy of the original AST before analysis
                    begin (opposite option is -no-copy)
-debug <n>          general level of debug
-dump-dependencies <s>  undocumented
-dump-interpreted-automata  dumps each interpreted automata built into a dot
                    file (opposite option is -no-dump-interpreted-automata)
-keep-temp-files    Keep temporary intermediate files (opposite option is
                    -no-keep-temp-files)
-kernel-debug <n>   level of debug for the Frama-C kernel (default to 0)
-orig-name          prints a message each time a variable is renamed
                    (opposite option is -no-orig-name)
-print-as-is        when pretty-printing C code, try to print it as close as
                    possible to the internal (Cil) representation (opposite
                    option is -no-print-as-is)

*** GETTING INFORMATION

--help              display a general help
-h                  alias for option --help
-help               alias for option --help
--list-plugins      display a general help
-plugins            alias for option --list-plugins
--plugins           alias for option --list-plugins
-autocomplete <p1,p2,...>  displays all Frama-C options, used for shell
                    autocompletion. Prints options for the specified plugin
                    names (or '@all' for all plugins). (preferably use
                    -autocomplete="p1,p2,...")
-explain            prints the help message for each option given in the
                    command line
-kernel-help        help of the Frama-C kernel
-kernel-h           alias for option -kernel-help
-print-config       print full config information
-print-config-json  prints extensive data about Frama-C's configuration, in
                    JSON format, and exits (experimental: the output format
                    is very likely to change in future versions).
-print-lib-path     print the path of the Frama-C kernel library
-print-libpath      alias for option -print-lib-path
-print-machdep      pretty print selected machdep
-print-machdep-builtin-macros  print on standard output the content of the
                    generated __fc_builtin_macros.h
-print-machdep-header  print on standard output the content of the generated
                    __fc_machdep.h
-print-plugin-path  print the path where the Frama-C dynamic plug-ins are
                    searched into
-print-share-path   print the Frama-C share path
-print-path         alias for option -print-share-path
-print-version      print the Frama-C version
-version            print the Frama-C version
-v                  alias for option -version
--version           alias for option -version

*** INPUT/OUTPUT SOURCE CODE

-ast-diff           creates a new project and computes a diff of the AST from
                    the current one (opposite option is -no-ast-diff)
-big-ints-hex <max>  display integers larger than <max> using hexadecimal
                    notation. A negative value disable this option. Disabled
                    by default.
-eager-load-sources  when loading a source, try to load all referenced
                    sources in memory (opposite option is
                    -no-eager-load-sources)
-float-print <default|norm|hex>  Control how floats will be printed :
                    'default' will print the float as is, 'norm' will use an
                    internal routine to normalize it using decimals, and
                    'hex' is the same than 'norm' but in hexadecimal. Default
                    value is 'default'
-keep-comments      try to keep comments in C code (opposite option is
                    -no-keep-comments)
-ocode <filename>   when printing code, redirects the output to file
                    <filename>
-print              pretty print C code (opposite option is -no-print)
-print-libc         when pretty-printing C code, keep prototypes coming from
                    Frama-C standard library (opposite option is
                    -no-print-libc)
-print-return       inline gotos to return statement (opposite option is
                    -no-print-return)
-typecheck          forces typechecking of the source files (set by default)

*** OUTPUT MESSAGES

-add-symbolic-path <path_1:name_1,...,path_n:name_n>  When displaying file
                    locations, replace (absolute) path with the corresponding
                    symbolic name (preferably use
                    -add-symbolic-path="path_1:name_1,...,path_n:name_n")
-kernel-log <K_1:file_1,...>  copy log messages from the Frama-C kernel to a
                    file. <K> is a combination of these characters:
                    a: ALL messages (equivalent to 'dfiruw')
                    d: debug       e: user or internal error (same as 'iu')
                    f: feedback    i: internal error
                    r: result      u: user error    w: warning
                    An empty <K> (e.g. ":file.txt") defaults to 'iruw'. One
                    plug-in can output to several files and vice-versa.
                    (preferably use -kernel-log="K_1:file_1,...")
-kernel-msg-key <k1[,...,kn]>  enables message display for categories
                    <k1>,...,<kn>. Use -kernel-msg-key help to get a list of
                    available categories, and * to enable all categories
                    (preferably use -kernel-msg-key="k1[,...,kn]")
-kernel-verbose <n>  level of verbosity for the Frama-C kernel (default to 1)
-kernel-warn-key <k1[=s1][,...,kn[=sn]]>  set warning status for category
                    <k1> to <s1>,...,<kn> to <sn>. Use -kernel-warn-key help
                    to get a list of available categories, and * to enable
                    all categories. Possible statuses are inactive, feedback,
                    warning, error, abort, feedback-once, warning-once,
                    error-once. Defaults to warning. (preferably use
                    -kernel-warn-key="k1[=s1][,...,kn[=sn]]")
-quiet              sets -verbose and -debug to 0
-time <filename>    append process time and timestamp to <filename> at exit
                    (preferably use -time="filename")
-tty                force the use of terminal capabilities for feedback; use
                    the opposite option for completely disabling the use of
                    terminal capabilities (opposite option is -no-tty)
-unicode            use utf8 in messages (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-unicode)
-verbose <n>        general level of verbosity

*** PARSING

-annot              read and parse annotations (set by default, opposite
                    option is -no-annot)
-audit-check <path>  reads an audit JSON file (produced by -audit-prepare)
                    and checks compliance w.r.t. it; e.g., if the source
                    files were declared and have the expected checksum.
                    Raises a warning (with warning key 'audit') in case of
                    failed checks. Requires -cpp-frama-c-compliant.
-audit-prepare <path>  produces audit-related information, such as the list
                    of all source files used during parsing (including those
                    in include directives) with checksums. Some plug-ins may
                    produce additional audit-related information. Prints the
                    information as JSON to the specified file, or if the file
                    is '-', prints as text to the standard output. Requires
                    -cpp-frama-c-compliant.
-cpp-command <cmd>  <cmd> is used to build the preprocessing command.
                    Default to $CPP environment variable or else "gcc -C -E
                    -I.".
                    If unset, the command is built as follows:
                    CPP -o <preprocessed file> <source file>
                    %1 and %2 can be used into CPP string to mark the
                    position of <source file> and <preprocessed file>
                    respectively (preferably use -cpp-command="cmd") [unsafe
                    in sandbox mode]
-cpp-extra-args <args>  additional arguments passed to the preprocessor
                    (mainly -D and -I) while preprocessing the C code but not
                    while preprocessing annotations (preferably use
                    -cpp-extra-args="args") [unsafe in sandbox mode]
-cpp-extra-args-per-file <file:flags>  when set, adds preprocessing arguments
                    for each specified file. To add arguments for all files,
                    use -cpp-extra-args. (preferably use
                    -cpp-extra-args-per-file="file:flags") [unsafe in sandbox
                    mode]
-cpp-frama-c-compliant  indicates that a custom preprocessor (see option
                    -cpp-command) accepts the same set of options as GNU cpp.
                    Set it to false if you have preprocessing issues with a
                    custom preprocessor. (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-cpp-frama-c-compliant)
-frama-c-stdlib     adds -I$FRAMAC_SHARE/libc to the options given to the cpp
                    command. If -cpp-frama-c-compliant is not false, also
                    adds -nostdinc to prevent inconsistent mix of system and
                    Frama-C header files (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-frama-c-stdlib)
-machdep <machine>  use <machine> as the current machine dependent
                    configuration. See "-machdep help" for a list. The
                    environment variable FRAMAC_MACHDEP can be used to
                    override the default value. The command line parameter
                    still has priority over the default value (preferably use
                    -machdep="machine")
-pp-annot           preprocess annotations (if they are read). Set by default
                    if the preprocessor is GNU-like (see option
                    -cpp-frama-c-compliant) (opposite option is -no-pp-annot)
-print-cpp-commands  prints the preprocessing command(s) used by Frama-C and
                    exits. (opposite option is -no-print-cpp-commands)
-register-attributes <k1:v1:v2,k2:v3,...>  Register an attribute so Frama-C
                    knows how to handle it. Keys are attribute names and
                    values are settings. It takes a list of attributes,
                    separated by commas, each followed by a list of settings
                    separated by colons, for example
                    'attr1:name:print:ignore,attr2:default'. The possible
                    setting values are:
                    - 'default': to register an attribute with default
                    settings. If the attribute is already registered, we use
                    its registered settings instead.
                    - 'name', 'type', 'funtype', 'stmt' or 'unknown': class
                    of the attribute that specifies on which AST node the
                    attribute should be attached. Defaults to unknown.
                    - 'print' or 'noprint': should the attribute be printed
                    when printing the AST? Debug key 'printer:attrs' ignores
                    this information. Defaults to print.
                    - 'ignore' or 'noignore': should the attribute be ignored
                    when comparing types? Defaults to 'ignore' if class is
                    'unknown' and 'noignore' otherwise.
                    Note: using the same setting category several times for
                    the same attribute is undefined. (preferably use
                    -register-attributes="k1:v1:v2,k2:v3,...")
-std <c11|c17|c23|c2y>  Configures the ISO standard to use. Note that your
                    preprocessor must support it, else it will lead to
                    preprocessing failure.

*** PERFORMANCE

-cache-size <n>     Control the amount of memory allocated to some internal
                    caches. Must be between 1 and 10; default value is 2.
                    Each increase of 1 doubles the size of these caches.
                    Small values are most suitable for the analysis of small
                    programs (less than 1000 lines). Higher values (around
                    7-8) can speed up the analysis of large code bases.
-memory-footprint <n>  Control the memory usage of Frama-C. With smaller
                    values, analyses consume much less memory but are also
                    slightly slower. Must be between 1 and 10; default is 6.
-pow-limit <max>    for performance reasons, limit the maximum exponent
                    accepted by pow functions in Z. Must be positive. Default
                    value is 99999

*** PROJECT-RELATED OPTIONS

-remove-projects <p1, ..., pn>  remove the given projects <p1>, ..., <pn>.
                    @all_but_current removes all projects but the current
                    one. (preferably use -remove-projects="p1, ..., pn")
-set-project-as-default  the current project becomes the default one (and so
                    future '-then' sequences are applied on it) (opposite
                    option is -no-set-project-as-default)

*** SAVING OR LOADING DATA

-autoload-plugins   Automatically load all plugins in FRAMAC_PLUGIN. (set by
                    default, opposite option is -no-autoload-plugins)
-cache <dir>        set the Frama-C cache directory to <dir>
-compress-saved-session  at exit, the session saved by the -save option is
                    compressed. No effect if the -save option is not used.
                    (set by default, opposite option is
                    -no-compress-saved-session)
-config <dir>       set the Frama-C config directory to <dir>
-load <filename>    load a previously-saved session from file <filename>
-load-library <libname,...>  Dynamically load libraries. Loading order is
                    preserved. Libraries are loaded between plugins and
                    modules. (preferably use -load-library="libname,...")
                    [unsafe in sandbox mode]
-load-module <SPEC,...>  Dynamically load modules. Each <SPEC> can be an
                    object file, with or without extension, or a Findlib
                    package. Loading order is preserved, but after plugins
                    and libraries. (preferably use -load-module="SPEC,...")
                    [unsafe in sandbox mode]
-load-plugin <plugin,...>  Dynamically load plugins. Loading order is
                    preserved. Plugins are loaded before libraries and
                    modules. (preferably use -load-plugin="plugin,...")
                    [unsafe in sandbox mode]
-save <filename>    at exit, save the session into file <filename>
-state <dir>        set the Frama-C state directory to <dir>

*** SEQUENCING OPTIONS

-commands-file <filename>  read the next command line arguments from the
                    given file. One argument per line. Start a line with # to
                    add a comment.
-then               parse options before `-then' and execute Frama-C
                    accordingly, then parse options after `-then' and
                    re-execute Frama-C
-then-last          like `-then', but the second group of actions is executed
                    on the last project created by a program transformer.
-then-on <p>        like `-then', but the second group of actions is executed
                    on project <p>
-then-replace       like `-then-last', but also remove the previous current
                    project.
